FILE: President Cyril Ramaphosa addresses Parliament during his Q&A session. CAPE TOWN - Opposition parties in parliament, have decided to seek a meeting with President Cyril Ramaphosa over pressing national issues. Political parties the UDM, DA, EFF, Freedom Front Plus, and the IFP met in Cape Town on Tuesday and agreed to seek an audience with Ramaphosa. The parties say they're concerned about the country's security, crime, and general lawlessness. READ | Police raid crime-infested areas of Pietermaritzburg Parties also want to meet parliamentary speaker Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula. They say they're concerned about the implementation of the Mpati and Zondo Commission recommendations.